<div id="review_2498405452" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2498405452" />
    <a title="Dana Sweeney" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29624880-dana-sweeney"><img alt="Dana Sweeney" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587961949p2/29624880.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2498405452?book_show_action=true">Aug 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dana Sweeney" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dana Sweeney" href="/user/show/29624880-dana-sweeney">Dana Sweeney</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2498405452" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17002072475313080729">One of the best, most searing plays I have ever read. This cements Arthur Miller in my mind as one of the most important American artists of the 20th century; he has a piercing, unnerving ability to reveal the ways we harm one another through group (in)action, how unconfronted histories destroy us, and how evil nearly always takes banal shapes cloaked in authority. <br/><br/>What Miller has to tell us about America and human behavior is as urgent in our time as it was in his own. I wish it was not so, but</span>
  <span id="freeText17002072475313080729" style="display:none">One of the best, most searing plays I have ever read. This cements Arthur Miller in my mind as one of the most important American artists of the 20th century; he has a piercing, unnerving ability to reveal the ways we harm one another through group (in)action, how unconfronted histories destroy us, and how evil nearly always takes banal shapes cloaked in authority. <br /><br />What Miller has to tell us about America and human behavior is as urgent in our time as it was in his own. I wish it was not so, but I am grateful to be able to read and re-read and reflect on his work. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17002072475313080729" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
