<div id="review_4094586481" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4094586481" />
    <a title="Andy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/105718645-andy"><img alt="Andy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608723453p2/105718645.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4094586481?book_show_action=true">Jul 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andy" href="/user/show/105718645-andy">Andy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141190020" href="/book/show/11914145-incident-at-vichy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/105718645-andy?shelf=plays">plays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/105718645-andy?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4094586481" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3866344858551281710">An excellent short play from Miller set around WWII. I am normally not a fan of historical fiction, but the way this play is set (In a &quot;police&quot; station) was very simple and unique. This play definitely captures emotions way more than his other works, mostly due to the prior knowledge of how Jews were treated at the time.<br/><br/>I really enjoyed seeing the characters and their theories on why they were arrested, Miller really captured the absurdity of the Nazi&apos;s and fascism. It was very nerve-wrecking wa</span>
  <span id="freeText3866344858551281710" style="display:none">An excellent short play from Miller set around WWII. I am normally not a fan of historical fiction, but the way this play is set (In a "police" station) was very simple and unique. This play definitely captures emotions way more than his other works, mostly due to the prior knowledge of how Jews were treated at the time.<br /><br />I really enjoyed seeing the characters and their theories on why they were arrested, Miller really captured the absurdity of the Nazi's and fascism. It was very nerve-wrecking watching the story unfold itself, especially when the main cast were wondering about their families.<br /><br />The ending was definitely unexpected and kinda sweet yet heartbreaking. Miller took a sensitive part of human history and very respectfully transformed it into a one-of-a-kind play. Easily one of his bests.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3866344858551281710" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


